                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d924">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00116 E.W./9–644: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Portugal</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lisbon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-06T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 6, 1944—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 6—3:58 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2755. ReEmbs 2703, September 1, 5 p.m.<note n="27" xml:id="d924fn27">Not
                        printed.</note> In conversation with Sampayo yesterday I again made
                    reference to the question of asylum for war criminals. Sampayo stated that note
                    had been taken of our position in this respect. He added that there was no
                    pending request before the Portuguese Government on the subject.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
